Moreover, the chemical environments of the three main elements C, N, and O were confirmed by high resolution XPS spectroscopy (Fig. 3
                        ). The peaks at 283.4, 284.2, 285.2, and 286.7 eV in the high-resolution C1s spectra of the 200-CDs were attributed to CC or CC, CN, CO, OCO, respectively (Fig. 3a). The high-resolution N1s peak of the 200-CDs presented three major peaks at 398.4, 399.3, and 400.6 eV corresponding to pyridinic N, pyrrolic N, and graphitic N, respectively (Fig. 3b). In addition, the high-resolution O1s spectrum exhibited two peaks, one at 530.5 eV, verifying the presence of COH or COC, and the other at 531.9 eV, verifying the presence of CO [30,31] (Fig. 3c). Similar findings were observed in high-resolution XPS spectra of the 250-CDs and 300-CDs (Fig. 3d-3i), except that the relative content of OCO and pyridinic N in the 300-CDs were higher than those found in the 200-CDs and 250-CDs (Fig. 3j and 3 h). The precise structure of the CDs was obtained by 1H NMR spectroscopy (Fig. 4
                        ). The signal peaks from 0.90 to 1.47 ppm correspond to the alkyl proton, and that at 3.07 ppm are attributed to the OCH proton. The signals around 3.84 ppm are due to 1H of methoxyl group. The peaks at 6–9 ppm are ascribed to ArH [32]. All CDs obtained at different roasting temperatures generally contained C, H, O, and N; however, the relative contents of the main elements varied. A greater nitrogen content was doped into the CDs from duck breasts at high temperatures. Abundant hydrophilic OH, CO, and NH2 groups were observed on the surface of the CDs, suggesting their good water solubility for further bio-imaging.
